diff:1620531748:1620531748:=1,73d0%0a%3c (:if authgroup @tas:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%3c %0a%3c >>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%3c %0a%3c [[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a%3c [[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]]%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%3c %0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c (:ifend:)%0a%3c %0a%3c [[!EndangeredLanguages]]%0a%3c %0a%3c !Lakota Language%0a%3c %0a%3c :Author: BrandonW%0a%3c %0a%3c '''Summary:''' \\%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#summary]]%0a%3c %0a%3c Looking at the endangered language Dakota%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#summaryends]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c [[#content]]%0a%3c %0a%3c On the EGIDS scale, Lakota is at level 6b, which means that the language is used for face-to-face communication by all generations, but users of Lakota is decreasing. One significant reason that the Lakota language is endangered is due to the need of cultural change. To revitalize the Lakota language, the languages needs to be taught to the younger generation.%0a%3c %0a%3c The Lakota people used to be a powerful group in the 16th century, so there was no need to change their culture. Americans started to show up in the 18th century, and at first the Lakota people did not need to change. But as more settlers intruded the area and more conflicts occurred, this lead to a battle where the US army defeated the Lakota in the Great Sioux War. Eventually, the Lakota people were forced to assimilate to the American culture as many of their old ways of living didn't exist anymore. Factors such as having worse military power, economics, and health care caused the shift for Lakota people to learn the American culture and English. This has lead to less users of the Lakota language.%0a%3c %0a%3c But, it seems possible that the Lakota language can be revitalized. Firstly, the Lakota people do not need to assimilate anymore to the American culture and the English language as territorial and governmental affairs have been solved. Harrison Puscher, the person who looked into the Lakota language and culture, believes that revitalizing the language would have to be done by teaching the younger generations. He proposes that an after-school group for elementary school kids be made that teaches the language and historical culture. As well, programs would be made for middle and high school students. Hopefully, this would lead to more interest in the language and make the Lakota language not endangered anymore.%0a%3c %0a%3c Source: https://www.colorado.edu/linguistics/2018/05/08/revitalizing-lakota-language%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c !!Expansions:%0a%3c [[#expansions]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#expansionsend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c %25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%3c %0a%3c (:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:else:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:ifend:)%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c !!Comments%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c (:section: C:)%0a%3c (:Category: EndangeredLanguages:)%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a
